# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ada-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace was the only legitimate child of poet Lord Byron and reformer Anne Isabella Milbanke.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lord Byron separated from his wife a month after Ada was born, and died when she was eight.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Although often ill in childhood, Lovelace pursued her studies assiduously.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] King was a Baron, and was created Viscount Ockham and 1st Earl of Lovelace in 1838.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The name Lovelace was chosen because Ada was descended from the extinct Baron Lovelaces.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The title given to her husband thus made Ada the Countess of Lovelace.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace's educational and social exploits brought her into contact with scientists such as Andrew Crosse, Charles Babbage, David Brewster, Charles Wheatstone and Michael Faraday, and the author Charles Dickens, contacts which she used to further her education.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace described her approach as "poetical science" and herself as an "Analyst (& Metaphysician)".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] When she was eighteen, Lovelace's mathematical talents led her to a long working relationship and friendship with fellow British mathematician Charles Babbage.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She was particularly interested in Babbage's work on the analytical engine.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace first met him on 5 June 1833, when she and her mother attended one of Charles Babbage's Saturday night soirées with their mutual friend, and Lovelace's private tutor, Mary Somerville.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Though Babbage's analytical engine was never constructed and did not influence the invention of electronic computers, it has been recognised as a Turing-complete general-purpose computer, which anticipated the essential features of a modern electronic computer.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Babbage is therefore known as the "father of computers," and Lovelace is credited with several computing "firsts" for her collaboration with him.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace translated an article by the military engineer Luigi Menabrea about the analytical engine, supplementing it with seven long explanatory notes.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] These described a method of using the machine to calculate Bernoulli numbers which is often called the first published computer program.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She developed a vision of the capability of computers to go beyond mere calculating or number-crunching, while many others, including Babbage, focused only on those capabilities.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace was the first to point out the possibility of encoding information besides mere arithmetical figures, such as music, and manipulating it with such a machine.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Her mindset of "poetical science" led her to ask questions about the analytical engine, examining how individuals and society relate to technology as a collaborative tool.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Ada is widely commemorated, including in the names of a programming language, roads, buildings and institutes, as well as programmes, lectures and courses.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] There are plaques, statues, paintings, literary and non-fiction works about her.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lord Byron expected his child to be a "glorious boy" and was disappointed when Lady Byron gave birth to a girl.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The child was named after Byron's half-sister, Augusta Leigh, and was called "Ada" by Byron himself.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] On 16 January 1816, at Lord Byron's command, Lady Byron left for her parents' home at Kirkby Mallory, taking their five-week-old daughter with her.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Although English law at the time granted full custody of children to the father in cases of separation, Lord Byron made no attempt to claim his parental rights, but did request that his sister keep him informed of Ada's welfare.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] On 21 April, Lord Byron signed the deed of separation, although very reluctantly, and left England for good a few days later.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Aside from an acrimonious separation, Lady Byron continued throughout her life to make allegations about her husband's immoral behaviour.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] This set of events made Lovelace infamous in Victorian society.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Ada did not have a relationship with her father.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] He died in April 1824 when she was eight years old.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Her mother was the only significant parental figure in her life.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace was not shown the family portrait of her father until her 20th birthday.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace did not have a close relationship with her mother.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She was often left in the care of her maternal grandmother Judith, Hon.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] However, because of societal attitudes of the time—which favoured the husband in any separation, with the welfare of any child acting as mitigation—Lady Byron had to present herself as a loving mother to the rest of society.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] This included writing anxious letters to Lady Milbanke about her daughter's welfare, with a cover note saying to retain the letters in case she had to use them to show maternal concern.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In one letter to Lady Milbanke, she referred to her daughter as "it": "I talk to it for your satisfaction, not my own, and shall be very glad when you have it under your own." Lady Byron had her teenage daughter watched by close friends for any sign of moral deviation.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace dubbed these observers the "Furies" and later complained they exaggerated and invented stories about her.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace was often ill, beginning in early childhood.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] At the age of eight, she experienced headaches that obscured her vision.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In June 1829, she was paralyzed after a bout of measles.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She was subjected to continuous bed rest for nearly a year, something which may have extended her period of disability.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] By 1831, she was able to walk with crutches.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Despite the illnesses, she developed her mathematical and technological skills.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Ada Byron had an affair with a tutor in early 1833.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She tried to elope with him after she was caught, but the tutor's relatives recognised her and contacted her mother.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lady Byron and her friends covered the incident up to prevent a public scandal.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace never met her younger half-sister, Allegra, the daughter of Lord Byron and Claire Clairmont.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Allegra died in 1822 at the age of five.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace did have some contact with Elizabeth Medora Leigh, the daughter of Byron's half-sister Augusta Leigh, who purposely avoided Lovelace as much as possible when introduced at court.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace became close friends with her tutor Mary Somerville, who introduced her to Charles Babbage in 1833.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She had a strong respect and affection for Somerville, and they corresponded for many years.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Other acquaintances included the scientists Andrew Crosse, Sir David Brewster, Charles Wheatstone, Michael Faraday and the author Charles Dickens.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She was presented at Court at the age of seventeen "and became a popular belle of the season" in part because of her "brilliant mind".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] By 1834 Ada was a regular at Court and started attending various events.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She danced often and was able to charm many people, and was described by most people as being dainty, although John Hobhouse, Byron's friend, described her as "a large, coarse-skinned young woman but with something of my friend's features, particularly the mouth".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] This description followed their meeting on 24 February 1834 in which Ada made it clear to Hobhouse that she did not like him, probably due to her mother's influence, which led her to dislike all of her father's friends.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] This first impression was not to last, and they later became friends.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] On 8 July 1835, she married William, 8th Baron King, becoming Lady King.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] They had three homes: Ockham Park, Surrey; a Scottish estate on Loch Torridon in Ross-shire; and a house in London.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] They spent their honeymoon at Ashley Combe near Porlock Weir, Somerset, which had been built as a hunting lodge in 1799 and was improved by King in preparation for their honeymoon.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] It later became their summer retreat and was further improved during this time.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] From 1845, the family's main house was Horsley Towers, built in the Tudorbethan fashion by the architect of the Houses of Parliament, Charles Barry, and later greatly enlarged to Lovelace's own designs.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] They had three children: Byron (born 1836); Anne Isabella (called Annabella, born 1837); and Ralph Gordon (born 1839).
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Immediately after the birth of Annabella, Lady King experienced "a tedious and suffering illness, which took months to cure".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Ada was a descendant of the extinct Barons Lovelace and in 1838, her husband was made Earl of Lovelace and Viscount Ockham, meaning Ada became the Countess of Lovelace.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 1843–44, Ada's mother assigned William Benjamin Carpenter to teach Ada's children and to act as a "moral" instructor for Ada.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] He quickly fell for her and encouraged her to express any frustrated affections, claiming that his marriage meant he would never act in an "unbecoming" manner.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] When it became clear that Carpenter was trying to start an affair, Ada cut it off.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 1841, Lovelace and Medora Leigh (the daughter of Lord Byron's half-sister Augusta Leigh) were told by Ada's mother that Ada's father was also Medora's father.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] On 27 February 1841, Ada wrote to her mother: "I am not in the least *astonished*.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She apparently lost more than £3,000 on the horses during the later 1840s.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The gambling led to her forming a syndicate with male friends, and an ambitious attempt in 1851 to create a mathematical model for successful large bets.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] This went disastrously wrong, leaving her thousands of pounds in debt to the syndicate, forcing her to admit it all to her husband.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She had a shadowy relationship with Andrew Crosse's son John from 1844 onwards.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] John Crosse destroyed most of their correspondence after her death as part of a legal agreement.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She bequeathed him the only heirlooms her father had personally left to her.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] During her final illness, she would panic at the idea of the younger Crosse being kept from visiting her.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] From 1832, when she was seventeen, her mathematical abilities began to emerge, and her interest in mathematics dominated the majority of her adult life.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Her mother's obsession with rooting out any of the insanity of which she accused Byron was one of the reasons that Ada was taught mathematics from an early age.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She was privately educated in mathematics and science by William Frend, William King, and Mary Somerville, the noted 19th-century researcher and scientific author.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In the 1840s, the mathematician Augustus De Morgan extended her "much help in her mathematical studies" including study of advanced calculus topics including the "numbers of Bernoulli" (that formed her celebrated algorithm for Babbage's Analytical Engine).
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In a letter to Lady Byron, De Morgan suggested that Ada's skill in mathematics might lead her to become "an original mathematical investigator, perhaps of first-rate eminence".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace often questioned basic assumptions through integrating poetry and science.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace believed that intuition and imagination were critical to effectively applying mathematical and scientific concepts.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She valued metaphysics as much as mathematics, viewing both as tools for exploring "the unseen worlds around us".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace died at the age of 36 on 27 November 1852 from cervical cancer (which contemporary accounts called uterine cancer, since a distinction between the two was not made at that time).
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The illness lasted several months, in which time Lady Byron took command over whom Ada saw, and excluded all of her friends and confidants.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Under her mother's influence, Ada had a religious transformation and was coaxed into repenting of her previous conduct and making Lady Byron her executor.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She lost contact with her husband after confessing something to him on 30 August which caused him to abandon her bedside.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She was buried, at her request, next to her father at the Church of St.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Mary Magdalene in Hucknall, Nottinghamshire.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Throughout her life, Lovelace was strongly interested in scientific developments and fads of the day, including phrenology and mesmerism.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] After her work with Babbage, Lovelace continued to work on other projects.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 1844, she commented to a friend Woronzow Greig about her desire to create a mathematical model for how the brain gives rise to thoughts and nerves to feelings ("a calculus of the nervous system").
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In part, her interest in the brain came from a long-running preoccupation, inherited from her mother, about her "potential" madness.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] As part of her research into this project, she visited the electrical engineer Andrew Crosse in 1844 to learn how to carry out electrical experiments.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In the same year, she wrote a review of a paper by Baron Karl von Reichenbach, *Researches on Magnetism*, but this was not published and does not appear to have progressed past the first draft.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 1851, the year before her cancer struck, she wrote to her mother mentioning "certain productions" she was working on regarding the relation of maths and music.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace first met Charles Babbage in June 1833, through their mutual friend Mary Somerville.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Later that month, Babbage invited Lovelace to see the prototype for his difference engine.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She became fascinated with the machine and used her relationship with Somerville to visit Babbage as often as she could.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Babbage was impressed by Lovelace's intellect and analytic skills.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] He called her "The Enchantress of Number".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 1840, Babbage was invited to give a seminar at the University of Turin about his Analytical Engine.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Luigi Menabrea, a young Italian engineer and the future Prime Minister of Italy, transcribed Babbage's lecture into French, and this transcript was subsequently published in the *Bibliothèque universelle de Genève* in October 1842.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Babbage's friend Charles Wheatstone commissioned Lovelace to translate Menabrea's paper into English.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] During a nine-month period in 1842–43, Lovelace translated Menabrea's article.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She augmented the paper with seven notes, A to G, about three times longer than the translation.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The translation and notes were then published in the September 1843 edition of Taylor's *Scientific Memoirs* under her initials *AAL*.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Explaining the Analytical Engine's function was a difficult task; many other scientists did not grasp the concept and the British establishment had shown little interest in it.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace's notes even had to explain how the Analytical Engine differed from the original Difference Engine.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Her work was well received at the time; the scientist Michael Faraday described himself as a supporter of her writing.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace and Babbage had a minor falling out when the papers were published, when he tried to leave his own statement (criticising the government's treatment of his Engine) as an unsigned preface, which could have been mistakenly interpreted as a joint declaration.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] When Taylor's *Scientific Memoirs* ruled that the statement should be signed, Babbage wrote to Lovelace asking her to withdraw the paper.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] This was the first that she knew he was leaving it unsigned, and she wrote back refusing to withdraw the paper.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The historian Benjamin Woolley theorised that "His actions suggested he had so enthusiastically sought Ada's involvement, and so happily indulged her ... because of her 'celebrated name'." Their friendship recovered, and they continued to correspond.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] On 12 August 1851, when she was dying of cancer, Lovelace wrote to him asking him to be her executor, though this letter did not give him the necessary legal authority.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Part of the terrace at Worthy Manor was known as *Philosopher's Walk;* it was there that Lovelace and Babbage were reputed to have walked while discussing mathematical principles.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The notes are important in the early history of computers, especially since Note G described, in complete detail, a method for calculating a sequence of Bernoulli numbers using the Analytical Engine, which might have run correctly had it ever been built.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Though Babbage's personal notes from 1837 to 1840 contain the first programs for the engine, the algorithm in Note G is often called the first published computer program.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The engine was never completed and so the program was never tested.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 1953, more than a century after her death, Ada Lovelace's notes on Babbage's Analytical Engine were republished as an appendix to B.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Bowden's *Faster than Thought: A Symposium on Digital Computing Machines*.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The engine has now been recognised as an early model for a computer and her notes as a description of a computer and software.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Based on this work, Lovelace is often called the first computer programmer and her method has been called the world's first computer program.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Eugene Eric Kim and Lovelace biographer, Betty Alexandra Toole, argued it was "incorrect" to regard Lovelace as the first computer programmer in an article for Scientific American.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Bromley notes several dozen sample programs prepared by Babbage between 1837 and 1840, all substantially predating Lovelace's notes.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Stein regards Lovelace's notes as "more a reflection of the mathematical uncertainty of the author, the political purposes of the inventor, and, above all, of the social and cultural context in which it was written, than a blueprint for a scientific development".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Bruce Collier wrote that Lovelace "made a considerable contribution to publicizing the Analytical Engine, but there is no evidence that she advanced the design or theory of it in any way".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Doron Swade has said that Ada only published the first computer program instead of actually writing it, but agrees that she was the only person to see the potential of the analytical engine as a machine capable of expressing entities other than quantities.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In his book, *Idea Makers*, Stephen Wolfram defends Lovelace's contributions.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] While acknowledging that Babbage wrote several unpublished algorithms for the Analytical Engine prior to Lovelace's notes, Wolfram argues that "there's nothing as sophisticated—or as clean—as Ada's computation of the Bernoulli numbers.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Babbage certainly helped and commented on Ada's work, but she was definitely the driver of it." Wolfram then suggests that Lovelace's main achievement was to distill from Babbage's correspondence "a clear exposition of the abstract operation of the machine—something which Babbage never did".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In her notes, Ada Lovelace emphasised the difference between the Analytical Engine and previous calculating machines, particularly its ability to be programmed to solve problems of any complexity.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She realised the potential of the device extended far beyond mere number crunching.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] This analysis was an important development from previous ideas about the capabilities of computing devices and anticipated the implications of modern computing one hundred years before they were realised.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] This objection has been the subject of much debate and rebuttal, including in the paper that originally coined it.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace recognized the difference between the details of the computing mechanism, as covered in an 1834 article on the Difference Engine, and the logical structure of the Analytical Engine, on which the article she was reviewing dwelt.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She noted that different specialists might be required in each area.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The computer language Ada, created on behalf of the United States Department of Defense, was named after Lovelace.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The reference manual for the language was approved on 10 December 1980 and the Department of Defense Military Standard for the language, *MIL-STD-1815*, was given the number of the year of her birth.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 1981, the Association for Women in Computing inaugurated its Ada Lovelace Award.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] As of 1998, the British Computer Society (BCS) has awarded the Lovelace Medal, and in 2008 initiated an annual competition for women students.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] BCSWomen sponsors the Lovelace Colloquium, an annual conference for women undergraduates.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 2013, the University of Deusto in Spain established the Ada Byron Award for women in technology, which was subsequently expanded to several Latin American countries.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Ada, the National College for Digital Skills, is a specialist college of further education and higher education in England, focused on digital skills.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The college has campuses in London (Pimlico) and Manchester (Ancoats).
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The college teaches degree-level apprenticeship, as well as a sixth-form college for students aged 16 to 19.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Ada Lovelace Day is an annual event celebrated on the second Tuesday of October, which began in 2009.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Its goal is to "... raise the profile of women in science, technology, engineering, and maths," and to "create new role models for girls and women" in these fields.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Events have included Wikipedia edit-a-thons with the aim of improving the representation of women on Wikipedia in terms of articles and editors to reduce unintended gender bias on Wikipedia.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The Ada Initiative was a non-profit organisation dedicated to increasing the involvement of women in the free culture and open source movements.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The building of the department of Engineering Mathematics at the University of Bristol is called the Ada Lovelace Building.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The Engineering in Computer Science and Telecommunications College building in Zaragoza University is called the Ada Byron Building.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The computer centre in the village of Porlock, near where Lovelace lived, is named after her.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Ada Lovelace House is a council-owned building in Kirkby-in-Ashfield, Nottinghamshire, near where Lovelace spent her infancy.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 2012, a Google Doodle and blog post honoured her on her birthday.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 2013, Ada Developers Academy was founded and named after her.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Its mission is to diversify tech by providing women and gender-diverse people the skills, experience, and community support to become professional software developers to change the face of tech.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] On 17 September 2013, the BBC Radio 4 biography programme *Great Lives* devoted an episode to Ada Lovelace; she was sponsored by TV presenter Konnie Huq.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] As of November 2015, all new British passports have included an illustration of Lovelace and Babbage.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 2017, a Google Doodle honoured her with other women on International Women's Day.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] On 2 February 2018, Satellogic, a high-resolution Earth observation imaging and analytics company, launched a ÑuSat type micro-satellite named in honour of Ada Lovelace.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In March 2018, *The New York Times* published a belated obituary for Ada Lovelace.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] On 27 July 2018, Senator Ron Wyden submitted, in the United States Senate, the designation of 9 October 2018 as National Ada Lovelace Day: "To honor the life and contributions of Ada Lovelace as a leading woman in science and mathematics".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The resolution (S.Res.592) was considered, and agreed to without amendment and with a preamble by unanimous consent.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In November 2020 it was announced that Trinity College Dublin, whose library had previously held forty busts, all of them of men, was commissioning four new busts of women, one of whom was to be Lovelace.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In March 2022, a statue of Ada Lovelace was installed at the site of the former Ergon House in the City of Westminster, London, honouring its scientific history.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The redevelopment was part of a complex with Imperial Chemical House.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The statue was sculpted by Etienne and Mary Millner and based on the portrait by Margaret Sarah Carpenter.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The sculpture was unveiled on International Women's Day, 2022.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] It stands on the 7th floor of Millbank Quarter overlooking the junction of Dean Bradley Street and Horseferry Road.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The 2022 graphics processor microarchitecture from Nvidia is named Ada Lovelace.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In 2025, the National Portrait Gallery acquired three images of Lovelace–the only known photographs of Lovelace.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Two were daguerreotypes by Antoine Claudet and were taken around 1843.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The third was by an unknown photographer and is of Henry Wyndham Phillips’ portrait of Lovelace.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In February 2026, a statue of Lovelace was unveiled on the Hinckley campus of the North Warwickshire and South Leicestershire College.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Special exhibitions were displayed by the Science Museum in London, England and the Weston Library (part of the Bodleian Library) in Oxford, England.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace is portrayed in Romulus Linney's 1977 play *Childe Byron*.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In Tom Stoppard's 1993 play *Arcadia*, the precocious teenage genius Thomasina Coverly—a character "apparently based" on Ada Lovelace (the play also involves Lord Byron)—comes to understand chaos theory, and theorises the second law of thermodynamics, before either is officially recognised.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In the 1990 steampunk novel *The Difference Engine* by William Gibson and Bruce Sterling, Lovelace delivers a lecture on the "punched cards" programme which proves Gödel's incompleteness theorems decades before their actual discovery.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace and Mary Shelley as teenagers are the central characters in Jordan Stratford's steampunk series, *The Wollstonecraft Detective Agency*.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace features in John Crowley's 2005 novel, *Lord Byron's Novel: The Evening Land*, as an unseen character whose personality is forcefully depicted in her annotations and anti-heroic efforts to archive her father's lost novel.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The 2015 play *Ada and the Engine* by Lauren Gunderson portrays Lovelace and Charles Babbage in unrequited love, and it imagines a post-death meeting between Lovelace and her father.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace and Babbage are also the main characters in Sydney Padua's webcomic and graphic novel *The Thrilling Adventures of Lovelace and Babbage*.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The comic features extensive footnotes on the history of Ada Lovelace, and many lines of dialogue are drawn from actual correspondence.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Poet Jessy Randall included a tribute to Lovelace in her 2025 collection of poems about women scientists, *The Path of Most Resistance*.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In the 1997 film *Conceiving Ada*, a computer scientist obsessed with Ada finds a way of communicating with her in the past by means of "undying information waves".
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace, identified as Ada Augusta Byron, is portrayed by Lily Lesser in the second series of *The Frankenstein Chronicles* aired on ITV in 2017.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] She is employed as an "analyst" to provide the workings of a life-sized humanoid automaton.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The brass workings of the machine are reminiscent of Babbage's analytical engine.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Her employment is described as keeping her occupied until she returns to her studies in advanced mathematics.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] "Lovelace" is the name of the operating system designed by the character Cameron Howe in *Halt and Catch Fire*, which aired on AMC in the US in 2015.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In the documentary *Calculating Ada: The Countess of Computing* (2015), Dr Hannah Fry covers the life of Ada Lovelace.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace and Babbage appear as characters in the second season of the ITV series *Victoria* (2017).
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Lovelace features as a character in "Spyfall, Part 2", the second episode of *Doctor Who*, series 12, which first aired on BBC One on 5 January 2020.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] The character was portrayed by Sylvie Briggs, alongside characterisations of Charles Babbage and Noor Inayat Khan.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Six copies of the 1843 first edition of *Sketch of the Analytical Engine* with Ada Lovelace's "Notes" have been located.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] Three are held at Harvard University, one at the University of Oklahoma, and one at the United States Air Force Academy.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] On 20 July 2018, the sixth copy was sold at auction to an anonymous buyer for £95,000.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] A digital facsimile of one of the copies in the Harvard University Library is available online.
[src:ada-deep/ada-lovelace] In December 2016, a letter written by Ada Lovelace was forfeited by Martin Shkreli to the New York State Department of Taxation and Finance for unpaid taxes owed by Shkreli.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada was originally designed by a team led by French computer scientist Jean Ichbiah of Honeywell under contract to the United States Department of Defense (DoD) from 1977 to 1983 to supersede over 450 programming languages then used by the DoD.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada was named after Ada Lovelace (1815–1852), who has been credited as the first computer programmer.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada was originally designed for embedded and real-time systems.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Tucker Taft of Intermetrics between 1992 and 1995, improved support for systems, numerical, financial, and object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Features of Ada include strong typing, modular programming mechanisms (packages), run-time checking, parallel processing (tasks, synchronous message passing, protected objects, and nondeterministic select statements), exception handling, and generics.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada 95 added support for object-oriented programming, including dynamic dispatch.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The syntax of Ada minimizes choices of ways to perform basic operations, and prefers English keywords (such as `or else` and `and then`) to symbols (such as `||` and `&&`).
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada uses the basic arithmetical operators `+`, `-`, `*`, and `/`, but avoids using other symbols.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Code blocks are delimited by words such as 'declare', 'begin', and 'end', where the 'end' (in most cases) is followed by the keyword of the block that it closes (e.g., `if` ...
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] In the case of conditional blocks this avoids a *dangling else* that could pair with the wrong nested 'if'-expression in other languages such as C or Java.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada is designed for developing very large software systems.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada packages can be compiled separately.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada package specifications (the package interface) can also be compiled separately without the implementation to check for consistency.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] This makes it possible to detect problems early during the design phase, before implementation starts.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] A large number of compile-time checks are supported to help avoid bugs that would not be detectable until run time in some other languages or would require explicit checks to be added to the source code.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] For example, the syntax requires explicitly named closing of blocks to prevent errors due to mismatched end tokens.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The adherence to strong typing allows detecting many common software errors (wrong parameters, range violations, invalid references, mismatched types, etc.) either during compile time, or otherwise during run time.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] As concurrency is part of the language specification, the compiler can in some cases detect potential deadlocks.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Compilers also commonly check for misspelled identifiers, visibility of packages, redundant declarations, etc. and can provide warnings and useful suggestions on how to fix the error.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada also supports run-time checks to protect against access to unallocated memory, buffer overflow errors, range violations, off-by-one errors, array access errors, and other detectable bugs.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] These checks can be disabled in the interest of runtime efficiency, but can often be compiled efficiently.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] It also includes facilities to help program verification.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] For these reasons, Ada is sometimes used in critical systems, where any anomaly might lead to very serious consequences, e.g., accidental death, injury or severe financial loss.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Examples of systems where Ada is used include avionics, air traffic control, railways, banking, military and space technology.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada's dynamic memory management is high-level and type-safe.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada has no generic or untyped pointers, nor does it implicitly declare any pointer type.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Instead, all dynamic memory allocation and deallocation must occur via explicitly declared *access types*.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Each access type has an associated *storage pool* that handles the low-level details of memory management; the programmer can either use the default storage pool or define new ones (this is particularly relevant for non-uniform memory access).
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] It is even possible to declare several different access types that all designate the same type but use different storage pools.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Also, the language provides for *accessibility checks*, both at compile time and at run time, that ensures that an *access value* cannot outlive the type of the object it points to.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Though the semantics of the language allow automatic garbage collection of inaccessible objects, most implementations do not support it by default, as it would cause unpredictable behaviour in real-time systems.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada supports a limited form of region-based memory management, and in Ada, destroying a storage pool also destroys all the objects in the pool.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] A double dash (`--`), resembling an em dash, denotes comment text.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Comments stop at end of line; there is intentionally no way to make a comment span multiple lines, to prevent unclosed comments from accidentally voiding whole sections of source code.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Disabling a whole block of code therefore requires the prefixing of each line (or column) individually with `--`.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] While this clearly denotes disabled code by creating a column of repeated '--' down the page, it also renders the experimental dis/re-enablement of large blocks a more drawn-out process in editors without block commenting support.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The semicolon (`;`) is a statement terminator, and the null or no-operation statement is `null;`.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] A single `;` without a statement to terminate is not allowed.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Unlike most ISO standards, the Ada language definition (known as the *Ada Reference Manual* or *ARM*, or sometimes the *Language Reference Manual* or *LRM*) is free content.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Thus, it is a common reference for Ada programmers, not only programmers implementing Ada compilers.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Apart from the reference manual, there is also an extensive rationale document which explains the language design and the use of various language constructs.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] This document is also widely used by programmers.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] When the language was revised, a new rationale document was written.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] One notable free software tool that is used by many Ada programmers to aid them in writing Ada source code is the GNAT Programming Studio, and GNAT which is part of the GNU Compiler Collection.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] In the 1970s the US Department of Defense (DoD) became concerned by the number of different programming languages being used for its embedded computer system projects, many of which were obsolete or hardware-dependent, and none of which supported safe modular programming.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] In 1975, a working group, the High Order Language Working Group (HOLWG), was formed with the intent to reduce this number by finding or creating a programming language generally suitable for the department's and the UK Ministry of Defence's requirements.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] After many iterations beginning with an original straw-man proposal the eventual programming language was named Ada.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The total number of high-level programming languages in use for such projects fell from over 450 in 1983 to 37 by 1996.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] HOLWG crafted the **Steelman language requirements**, a series of documents stating the requirements they felt a programming language should satisfy.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Many existing languages were formally reviewed, but the team concluded in 1977 that no existing language met the specifications.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The requirements were created by the United States Department of Defense in *The Department of Defense Common High Order Language program* in 1978.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The predecessors of this document were called, in order, "Strawman", "Woodenman", "Tinman" and "Ironman".
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The requirements focused on the needs of embedded computer applications, and emphasised reliability, maintainability, and efficiency.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Notably, they included exception handling facilities, run-time checking, and parallel computing.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] It was concluded that no existing language met these criteria to a sufficient extent, so a contest was called to create a language that would be closer to fulfilling them.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The design that won this contest became the Ada programming language.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The resulting language followed the Steelman requirements closely, though not exactly.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] In April 1978, after public scrutiny, the Red and Green proposals passed to the next phase.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] In May 1979, the Green proposal, designed by Jean Ichbiah at Honeywell, was chosen and given the name Ada—after Augusta Ada King, Countess of Lovelace, usually known as Ada Lovelace.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] This proposal was influenced by the language LIS that Ichbiah and his group had developed in the 1970s.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The preliminary Ada reference manual was published in ACM SIGPLAN Notices in June 1979.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The Military Standard reference manual was approved on December 10, 1980 (Ada Lovelace's birthday), and given the number MIL-STD-1815 in honor of Ada Lovelace's birth year.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] In 1981, Tony Hoare took advantage of his Turing Award speech to criticize Ada for being overly complex and hence unreliable, but subsequently seemed to recant in the foreword he wrote for an Ada textbook.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada attracted much attention from the programming community as a whole during its early days.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Its backers and others predicted that it might become a dominant language for general purpose programming and not only defense-related work.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ichbiah publicly stated that within ten years, only two programming languages would remain: Ada and Lisp.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Early Ada compilers struggled to implement the large, complex language, and both compile-time and run-time performance tended to be slow and tools primitive.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Compiler vendors expended most of their efforts in passing the massive, language-conformance-testing, government-required Ada Compiler Validation Capability (ACVC) validation suite that was required in another novel feature of the Ada language effort.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The first validated Ada implementation was the NYU Ada/Ed translator, certified on April 11, 1983.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] NYU Ada/Ed is implemented in the high-level set language SETL.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Several commercial companies began offering Ada compilers and associated development tools, including Alsys, TeleSoft, DDC-I, Advanced Computer Techniques, Tartan Laboratories, Irvine Compiler, TLD Systems, and Verdix.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] In 1991, the US Department of Defense began to require the use of Ada (the *Ada mandate*) for all software, though exceptions to this rule were often granted.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The Department of Defense Ada mandate was effectively removed in 1997, as the DoD began to embrace commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) technology.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Similar requirements existed in other NATO countries: Ada was required for NATO systems involving command and control and other functions, and Ada was the mandated or preferred language for defense-related applications in countries such as Sweden, Germany, and Canada.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] By the late 1980s and early 1990s, Ada compilers had improved in performance, but there were still barriers to fully exploiting Ada's abilities, including a tasking model that was different from what most real-time programmers were used to.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The Canadian Automated Air Traffic System was written in 1 million lines of Ada (SLOC count).
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] It featured advanced distributed processing, a distributed Ada database, and object-oriented design.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada is also used in other air traffic systems, e.g., the UK's next-generation Interim Future Area Control Tools Support (iFACTS) air traffic control system is designed and implemented using SPARK Ada.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] It is also used in the French TVM in-cab signalling system on the TGV high-speed rail system, and the metro suburban trains in Paris, London, Hong Kong and New York City.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The Ada 95 revision of the language went beyond the Steelman requirements, targeting general-purpose systems in addition to embedded ones, and adding features supporting object-oriented programming.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada was first published in 1980 as an ANSI standard ANSI/**MIL-STD 1815**.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] As this very first version held many errors and inconsistencies, the revised edition was published in 1983 as ANSI/MIL-STD 1815A.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Without any further changes, it became an ISO standard in 1987.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] This version of the language is commonly known as **Ada 83**, from the date of its adoption by ANSI, but is sometimes referred to also as **Ada 87**, from the date of its adoption by ISO.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] There is also a French translation; DIN translated it into German as DIN 66268 in 1988.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Work has continued on improving and updating the technical content of the Ada language.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] A Technical Corrigendum to Ada 95 was published in October 2001, and a major Amendment, ISO/IEC 8652:1995/Amd 1:2007 was published on March 9, 2007, commonly known as **Ada 2005** because work on the new standard was finished that year.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The Ada-based SPARK technology has been made possible by the enabling characteristics of the Ada language, including its separation of specification and implementation via packages, its support for user-defined scalar types, and its support for composite type usage without resorting to pointers.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The Ada 2012 revision was especially important for SPARK, as its support for contracts as a part of the language permitted SPARK to be redesigned from the beginning towards fulfilling its goal of co-developing programs alongside their proofs of correctness.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] On May 2, 2023, the Ada community saw the formal approval of publication of the **Ada 2022** edition of the programming language standard.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Despite the names Ada 83, 95 etc., legally there is only one Ada standard, the last ISO/IEC standard: with the acceptance of a new standard version, the previous one becomes withdrawn.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The other names are informal ones referencing a certain edition.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Other related standards include ISO/IEC 8651-3:1988 *Information processing systems—Computer graphics—Graphical Kernel System (GKS) language bindings—Part 3: Ada*.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada is an ALGOL-like programming language featuring control structures with reserved words such as *if*, *then*, *else*, *while*, *for*, and so on.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] However, Ada also has many data structuring facilities and other abstractions which were not included in the original ALGOL 60, such as type definitions, records, pointers, and enumerations.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Such constructs were in part inherited from or inspired by Pascal.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada's type system is not based on a set of predefined primitive types but allows users to declare their own types.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] This declaration in turn is not based on the internal representation of the type but on describing the goal which should be achieved.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] This allows the compiler to determine a suitable memory size for the type, and to check for violations of the type definition at compile time and run time (i.e., range violations, buffer overruns, type consistency, etc.).
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada supports numerical types defined by a range, modulo types, aggregate types (records and arrays), and enumeration types.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Access types define a reference to an instance of a specified type; untyped pointers are not permitted.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Special types provided by the language are task types and protected types.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] The predefined plus operator can only add values of the same type, so the expression is illegal.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Types can have modifiers such as *limited, abstract, private* etc.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Private types do not show their inner structure; objects of limited types cannot be copied.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada 95 adds further features for object-oriented extension of types.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Ada is a structured programming language, meaning that the flow of control is structured into standard statements.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] All standard constructs and deep-level early exit are supported, so the use of the also supported "go to" commands is seldom needed.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Among the parts of an Ada program are packages, procedures and functions.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Functions differ from procedures in that they must return a value.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Function calls cannot be used "as a statement", and their result must be assigned to a variable.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] However, since Ada 2012, functions are not required to be pure and may mutate their suitably declared parameters or the global state.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Packages, procedures and functions can nest to any depth, and each can also be the logical outermost block.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Each package, procedure or function can have its own declarations of constants, types, variables, and other procedures, functions and packages, which can be declared in any order.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] A pragma is a compiler directive that conveys information to the compiler to allow specific manipulating of compiled output.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Certain pragmas are built into the language, while others are implementation-specific.
[src:ada-deep/ada-programming-language] Examples of common usage of compiler pragmas would be to disable certain features, such as run-time type checking or array subscript boundary checking, or to instruct the compiler to insert object code instead of a function call (as C/C++ does with inline functions).
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] In the context of hardware and software systems, **formal verification** is the act of proving or disproving the correctness of a system with respect to a certain formal specification or property, using formal methods of mathematics.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Formal verification is a key incentive for formal specification of systems, and is at the core of formal methods.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] It represents an important dimension of analysis and verification in electronic design automation and is one approach to software verification.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] The use of formal verification enables the highest Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL7) in the framework of common criteria for computer security certification.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Formal verification can be helpful in proving the correctness of systems such as: cryptographic protocols, combinational circuits, digital circuits with internal memory, and software expressed as source code in a programming language.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Prominent examples of verified software systems include the CompCert verified C compiler and the seL4 high-assurance operating system kernel.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] The verification of these systems is done by ensuring the existence of a formal proof of a mathematical model of the system.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Model checking involves a systematic and exhaustive exploration of the mathematical model.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Such exploration is possible for finite models, but also for some infinite models, where infinite sets of states can be effectively represented finitely by using abstraction or taking advantage of symmetry.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Usually, this consists of exploring all states and transitions in the model, by using smart and domain-specific abstraction techniques to consider whole groups of states in a single operation and reduce computing time.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Implementation techniques include state space enumeration, symbolic state space enumeration, abstract interpretation, symbolic simulation, abstraction refinement.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] The properties to be verified are often described in temporal logics, such as linear temporal logic (LTL), Property Specification Language (PSL), SystemVerilog Assertions (SVA), or computational tree logic (CTL).
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Another approach is deductive verification.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Formal verification of software programs involves proving that a program satisfies a formal specification of its behavior.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Subareas of formal verification include deductive verification (see above), abstract interpretation, automated theorem proving, type systems, and lightweight formal methods.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] A promising type-based verification approach is dependently typed programming, in which the types of functions include (at least part of) those functions' specifications, and type-checking the code establishes its correctness against those specifications.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Fully featured dependently typed languages support deductive verification as a special case.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Another complementary approach is program derivation, in which efficient code is produced from functional specifications by a series of correctness-preserving steps.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] An example of this approach is the Bird–Meertens formalism, and this approach can be seen as another form of program synthesis.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] These techniques can be *sound*, meaning that the verified properties can be logically deduced from the semantics, or *unsound*, meaning that there is no such guarantee.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] A sound technique yields a result only once it has covered the entire space of possibilities.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] An example of an unsound technique is one that covers only a subset of the possibilities, for instance only integers up to a certain number, and give a "good-enough" result.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Techniques can also be *decidable*, meaning that their algorithmic implementations are guaranteed to terminate with an answer, or undecidable, meaning that they may never terminate.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] By bounding the scope of possibilities, unsound techniques that are decidable might be able to be constructed when no decidable sound techniques are available.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Verification is one aspect of testing a product's fitness for purpose.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Often one refers to the overall checking process as V & V.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] The verification process consists of static/structural and dynamic/behavioral aspects.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] E.g., for a software product one can inspect the source code (static) and run against specific test cases (dynamic).
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Validation usually can be done only dynamically, i.e., the product is tested by putting it through typical and atypical usages ("Does it satisfactorily meet all use cases?").
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Program repair is performed with respect to an oracle, encompassing the desired functionality of the program which is used for validation of the generated fix.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] A simple example is a test-suite—the input/output pairs specify the functionality of the program.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] A variety of techniques are employed, most notably using satisfiability modulo theories (SMT) solvers, and genetic programming, using evolutionary computing to generate and evaluate possible candidates for fixes.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] The former method is deterministic, while the latter is randomized.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] For example, the Nopol tool encodes the repair of buggy conditional statements as an SMT instance to determinstically generate patches for if conditions and missing preconditions.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Program repair combines techniques from formal verification and program synthesis.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Fault-localization techniques in formal verification are used to compute program points which might be possible bug-locations, which can be targeted by the synthesis modules.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Repair systems often focus on a small pre-defined class of bugs in order to reduce the search space.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Industrial use is limited owing to the computational cost of existing techniques.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] The growth in complexity of designs increases the importance of formal verification techniques in the hardware industry.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] At present, formal verification is used by most or all leading hardware companies, but its use in the software industry is still languishing.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] This could be attributed to the greater need in the hardware industry, where errors have greater commercial significance.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Because of the potential subtle interactions between components, it is increasingly difficult to exercise a realistic set of possibilities by simulation.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Important aspects of hardware design are amenable to automated proof methods, making formal verification easier to introduce and more productive.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] As of 2011, several operating systems have been formally verified: NICTA's Secure Embedded L4 microkernel, sold commercially as seL4 by OK Labs; OSEK/VDX based real-time operating system ORIENTAIS by East China Normal University; Green Hills Software's Integrity operating system; and SYSGO's PikeOS.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] In 2016, a team led by Zhong Shao at Yale developed a formally verified operating system kernel called CertiKOS.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] As of 2017, formal verification has been applied to the design of large computer networks through a mathematical model of the network, and as part of a new network technology category, intent-based networking.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] Network software vendors that offer formal verification solutions include Cisco Forward Networks and Veriflow Systems.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] The SPARK programming language provides a toolset which enables software development with formal verification and is used in several high-integrity systems.
[src:ada-deep/formal-verification] The CompCert C compiler is a formally verified C compiler implementing the majority of ISO C.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] Ichbiah was a descendant of Greek and Turkish Jews from Thessaloniki who emigrated to France.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] In 1980, Ichbiah founded the software development company Alsys, created to support initial work on the Ada programming language.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] In July 1995, Alsys merged to become Thomson Software Products (TSP), which itself would subsequently merge into Aonix in 1996.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] From 1972 to 1974, Ichbiah worked on designing an experimental system implementation language called LIS, based on Pascal and Simula.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] He had been chairman of the Simula User's Group and was one of the founding members of IFIP WG 2.4 on Systems Implementation Languages.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] Ichbiah then joined CII Honeywell Bull (CII-HB) in Louveciennes, France, becoming a member of the Programming Research division.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] Among other projects, he worked on the rewrite of the Siris 7 operating system into Siris 8 ,Mainframe computer CII Iris 80 developed by the French company CII.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] Ichbiah's team submitted a language design labelled "Green" to a competition to choose the United States Department of Defense's embedded programming language.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] When Green was selected in 1978, he continued as chief designer of the language, now named "Ada".
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] In 1980, Ichbiah left CII-HB and founded the Alsys corporation in La Celle-Saint-Cloud, which continued language definition to standardize Ada 83, and later went into the Ada compiler business, also supplying special validated compiler systems to NASA, the US Army, and others.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] He later moved to the Waltham, Massachusetts subsidiary of Alsys.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] In the 1990s, Ichbiah designed the keyboard layout FITALY, which is specifically optimized for stylus or touch-based input.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] Subsequently, he started the Textware Solutions company, which sells text entry software for PDAs and tablet PCs, as well as text-entry software for medical transcription on PCs.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] In 1979, Jean Ichbiah was designated a *chevalier* (knight) of the French Legion of Honour and a *correspondent* of the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] He received a Certificate of Distinguished Service from the United States Department of Defense for his work on Ada.
[src:ada-deep/jean-ichbiah] Jean Ichbiah died from complications of a brain tumor on January 26, 2007.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:ada-deep/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] Originally, three versions of SPARK existed (SPARK83, SPARK95, SPARK2005), based on Ada 83, Ada 95, and Ada 2005 respectively.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] A fourth version, SPARK 2014, based on Ada 2012, was released on April 30, 2014.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] SPARK 2014 is a complete re-design of the language and supports software verification tools.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] The SPARK language consists of a well-defined subset of the Ada language that uses contracts to describe the specification of components in a form that is suitable for both static and dynamic verification.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] SPARK is also designed to eliminate all language constructs that can cause unpredictable behavior.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] In SPARK83/95/2005, the contracts are encoded in Ada comments and so are ignored by any standard Ada compiler, but are processed by the SPARK *Examiner* and its associated tools.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] These earlier versions focus on static verification of contracts.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] SPARK 2014, in contrast, uses Ada 2012's built-in syntax of *aspects* to express contracts, bringing them into the core of the language.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] The main tool for SPARK 2014 (GNATprove) is based on the GNAT/GCC infrastructure, and re-uses almost all of the GNAT Ada 2012 front-end.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] SPARK utilises the strengths of Ada while trying to eliminate all its potential ambiguities and insecure constructs.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] SPARK programs are by design meant to be unambiguous, and their behavior is required to be unaffected by the choice of Ada compiler.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] These goals are achieved partly by omitting some of Ada's more problematic features (such as unrestricted parallel tasking) and partly by introducing contracts that encode the application designer's intentions and requirements for certain components of a program.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] In pure Ada, this might increment the variable `X` by one or one thousand; or it might set some global counter to `X` and return the original value of the counter in `X`; or it might do nothing with `X`.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] With SPARK 2014, contracts are added to the code to provide more information regarding what a subprogram actually does.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] This specifies that the `Increment` procedure uses no (neither update nor read) global variable and that the only data item used in calculating the new value of `X` is `X` alone.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] If GNATprove is then run on the specification and corresponding body of a subprogram, it will analyse the body of the subprogram to build up a model of the information flow.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] This model is then compared against what has been specified by the annotations and any discrepancies reported to the user.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] These specifications can be further extended by asserting various properties that either need to hold when a subprogram is called (*preconditions*) or that will hold once execution of the subprogram has completed (*postconditions*).
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] GNATprove can also generate a set of verification conditions (VCs).
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] These are used to establish whether certain properties hold for a given subprogram.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] If a postcondition or any other assertion is added to a subprogram, GNATprove will also generate VCs that require the user to show that these properties hold for all possible paths through the subprogram.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] Under the hood, GNATprove uses the Why3 intermediate language and VC Generator, and the CVC4, Z3, and Alt-Ergo theorem provers to discharge VCs.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] Use of other provers (including interactive proof checkers) is also possible through other components of the Why3 toolset.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] The beginnings of the technology go back to 1987, based on work done at the University of Southampton.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] The first version of SPARK (based on Ada 83) was produced at the university, with UK Ministry of Defence sponsorship, by Bernard Carré and Trevor Jennings.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] The name *SPARK* was derived from *SPADE Ada Kernel*, in reference to the *SPADE* subset of the Pascal programming language.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] Subsequently the language was progressively extended and refined, first by Program Validation Limited and then by Praxis Critical Systems Limited.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] In 2004, Praxis Critical Systems Limited changed its name to Praxis High Integrity Systems Limited, and work on SPARK continued.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] In January 2010, the company became Altran Praxis.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] In early 2009, Praxis formed a partnership with AdaCore, and released *SPARK Pro* under the terms of the GPL.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] This was followed in June 2009 by the SPARK GPL Edition 2009, aimed at the free and open-source software (FOSS) and academic communities.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] In January 2013, Altran-Praxis changed its name to Altran, which in April 2021 became Capgemini Engineering (following Altran's merger with Capgemini).
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] The first Pro release of SPARK 2014 was announced on April 30, 2014, and was quickly followed by the SPARK 2014 GPL edition, aimed at the FLOSS and academic communities.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] SPARK has been employed in a number of real-world industrial uses.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] Incorporating it as early in the design process as possible is seen as generally giving the most favorable result.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] In terms of the approval processes necessary for such systems, SPARK has been used to certify against the UK Defense standard (DEFSTAN) 00-55, as well as to the DO-178B Level A and ITSEC E6.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] SPARK has also been used in secure systems development.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] Users include Rockwell Collins (Turnstile and SecureOne cross-domain solutions), the development of the original MULTOS CA, the NSA Tokeneer demonstrator, the secunet multi-level workstation, the Muen separation kernel and Genode block-device encrypter.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] Another case was implemented a secure Certificate Authority for the stored-value card produced by Mondex International, in which Z notation was used as a precursor to the coding in SPARK.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] In August 2010, Rod Chapman, principal engineer of Altran Praxis, implemented Skein, one of the SHA-3 candidates, in SPARK.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] After careful optimization, he managed to have the SPARK version run only about 5 to 10% slower than the C implementation.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] Later improvements to the Ada middle-end in GCC (implemented by Eric Botcazou of AdaCore) closed the gap, with the SPARK code matching the C in performance exactly.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] NVIDIA have also adopted SPARK for the implementation of security-critical firmware.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] Finding success in this, the company added SPARK for extra firmware-related projects and began in-house training in use of the SPARK technology.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] In 2020, Rod Chapman re-implemented the TweetNaCl cryptographic library in SPARK 2014.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] The SPARK version of the library has a complete auto-active proof of type-safety, memory-safety and some correctness properties, and retains constant-time algorithms throughout.
[src:ada-deep/spark-programming-language] The SPARK code is also significantly faster than TweetNaCl.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Headquartered at the Pentagon in Arlington County, Virginia, just outside Washington, D.C., the stated mission of the Department of Defense is "to provide the military forces needed to deter war and ensure our nation's security".
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Department of Defense is headed by the secretary of defense, a cabinet-level official who reports directly to the president of the United States.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The president is commander-in-chief of the U.S.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Within the Department of Defense are three subordinate military departments: the Department of the Army, the Department of the Navy, and the Department of the Air Force.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] In addition, four national intelligence services are part of the Department of Defense: the Defense Intelligence Agency, National Security Agency (NSA), National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency, and National Reconnaissance Office.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Additionally, the Defense Contract Management Agency is responsible for administering contracts for the Department of Defense.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Military operations are managed by eleven regional or functional unified combatant commands.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Department of Defense also operates several joint services schools, including the Eisenhower School and the National War College.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] As of November 2022, the department has over 1.4 million active-duty uniformed personnel in the six armed services, and over 747,000 civilian employees.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] It also supervises over 778,000 National Guard and reservist personnel.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Faced with rising tensions between the Thirteen Colonies and the British government, one of the first actions taken by the First Continental Congress in September 1774 was to recommend that the colonies begin defensive military preparations.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] In mid-June 1775, after the outbreak of the Revolutionary War, the Second Continental Congress, recognizing the necessity of having a national army that could move about and fight beyond the boundaries of any particular colony, organized the Continental Army on 14 June 1775.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Later that year, Congress would charter the Continental Navy on 13 October, and the Continental Marines on 10 November.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Congress on 4 March 1789, legislation to create a military defense force stagnated as they focused on other concerns relevant to setting up the new government.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] President George Washington went to Congress to remind them of their duty to establish a military twice during this time.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Finally, on the last day of the session, 29 September 1789, Congress created the War Department.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The War Department handled naval affairs until Congress created the Navy Department in 1798.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The secretaries of each department reported directly to the president as cabinet-level advisors until 1949, when all military departments became subordinate to the Secretary of Defense.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] After the end of World War II, President Harry Truman proposed the creation of a unified department of national defense.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] In a special message to the Congress on 19 December 1945, the president cited wasteful military spending and interdepartmental conflicts.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Deliberations in Congress went on for months focusing heavily on the role of the military in society and the threat of granting too much military power to the executive.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The NME was placed under the control of the new post of secretary of defense.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The National Military Establishment formally began operations on 18 September, the day after the Senate confirmed James V.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Forrestal as the first secretary of defense.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The National Military Establishment was renamed the "Department of Defense" on 10 August 1949, and absorbed the three cabinet-level military departments, in an amendment to the original 1947 law.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Under the Department of Defense Reorganization Act of 1958 (Pub.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] 85–599), channels of authority within the department were streamlined while still maintaining the ordinary jurisdiction of the Military Departments to organize, train, and equip their associated forces.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Act clarified the overall decision-making authority of the secretary of defense concerning these subordinate military departments.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] It more clearly defined the operational chain of command over U.S. military forces (created by the military departments) as running from the president to the secretary of defense, the service chief of the unified combatant commanders, and then to the unified combatant commanders.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Also provided in this legislation was a centralized research authority, the Advanced Research Projects Agency, eventually known as DARPA.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The act was written and promoted by the Eisenhower administration and was signed into law on 6 August 1958.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] By the National Security Act of 1947, the Department of the Navy and the Department of War had a new single Secretary imposed over the top of their two previously independent Cabinet secretaries.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The War Department also changed its name to the Department of the Army and split off the Department of the Air Force.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The new Cabinet-level department was initially designated the National Military Establishment (NME).
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] On 10 August 1949, the National Security Act of 1947 was amended; the amendment renamed the NME the Department of Defense.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The renaming is alleged to be due to the NME's pronunciation as "enemy".
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Four people told the *The New York Times* that Anduril Industries co-founder Palmer Luckey suggested to president-elect Donald Trump, before his second inauguration, that he change the name to the "Department of War".
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] On 5 September 2025, Trump signed an executive order authorizing "Department of War" and "secretary of war" as secondary titles to the main titles of "Department of Defense" and "secretary of defense".
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The terms must be accommodated by federal agencies and are permitted in executive branch communications, ceremonial settings, and non-statutory documents.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] However, only an act of Congress can legally and formally change the department's name and secretary's title, so "Department of Defense" and "secretary of defense" remain legally official.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Trump described his rebranding as an effort to project a stronger and more bellicose name and said the "defense" names were "woke".
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] On 11 June 2026, the House Armed Services Committee and Senate Armed Services Committee voted to change the name to the Department of War as part of the 2027 National Defense Authorization Act.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Congressional Budget Office estimated that the change of name could cost between $10 million and $125 million, depending on the depth of implementation.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Because the Constitution vests all military authority in Congress and the president, the statutory authority of the secretary of defense is derived from their constitutional authority.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Since it is impractical for either Congress or the president to participate in every piece of Department of Defense affairs, the secretary of defense and the secretary's subordinate officials generally exercise military authority.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Department of Defense Directive 5100.01 describes the organizational relationships within the department and is the foundational issuance for delineating the major functions of the department.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The latest version, signed by then–secretary of defense Robert Gates in December 2010, is the first major re-write since 1987.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Office of the Secretary of Defense (OSD) is the secretary and their deputies, including predominantly civilian staff.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] OSD also performs oversight and management of the Defense Agencies, Department of Defense Field Activities, and specialized Cross Functional Teams.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Several defense agencies are members of the United States Intelligence Community.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] These are national-level intelligence services that operate under the Department of Defense jurisdiction but simultaneously fall under the authorities of the Office of the Director of National Intelligence.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] They fulfill the requirements of national policymakers and war planners, serve as Combat Support Agencies, and also assist and deploy alongside non-Department of Defense intelligence or law enforcement services such as the Central Intelligence Agency and the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The military services each have their intelligence elements that are distinct from but subject to coordination by national intelligence agencies under the Department of Defense.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Department of Defense manages the nation's coordinating authorities and assets in disciplines of signals intelligence, geospatial intelligence, and measurement and signature intelligence, and also builds, launches, and operates the Intelligence Community's satellite assets.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Department of Defense also has its own human intelligence service, which contributes to the CIA's human intelligence efforts while also focusing on military human intelligence priorities.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] These agencies are directly overseen by the under secretary of defense for intelligence and security.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Joint Chiefs of Staff is a body of senior uniformed leaders in the Department of Defense who advise the secretary of defense, the Homeland Security Council, the National Security Council and the president on military matters.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Each of the individual military service chiefs, outside their Joint Chiefs of Staff obligations, works directly for the secretary of the military department concerned: the secretary of the Army, secretary of the Navy, and secretary of the Air Force.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Following the Goldwater–Nichols Act in 1986, the Joint Chiefs of Staff no longer maintained operational command authority individually or collectively.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The act designated the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff (CJCS) as the "principal military adviser to the president, the National Security Council, the Homeland Security Council, and the Secretary of Defense".
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The remaining Joint Chiefs of Staff may only have their advice relayed to the president, National Security Council, the Homeland Security Council, or the secretary of defense after submitting it to the CJCS.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] By law, the chairman has to present that advice whenever he is presenting his own.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The chain of command goes from the president to the secretary of defense to the commanders of the Combatant Commands.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Goldwater–Nichols also created the office of vice-chairman, and the chairman is now designated as the *principal military adviser* to the secretary of defense, the Homeland Security Council, the National Security Council and to the president.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Joint Staff is a headquarters staff at the Pentagon made up of personnel from all five services that assist the chairman and vice chairman in discharging their duties.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] It is managed by the director of the Joint Staff who is a lieutenant general or vice admiral.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] 2. the Department of the Navy, within which the United States Navy and the United States Marine Corps are organized.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] 3. the Department of the Air Force, within which the United States Air Force and United States Space Force are organized.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The military departments are each headed by their secretary (i.e., Secretary of the Army, Secretary of the Navy and Secretary of the Air Force), appointed by the president, with the advice and consent of the Senate.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] They have the legal authority under Title 10 of the United States Code to conduct all the affairs of their respective departments within which the military services are organized.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The secretaries of the military departments are (by law) subordinate to the secretary of defense and (by SecDef delegation) to the deputy secretary of defense.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Military departments are tasked solely with "the training, provision of equipment, and administration of troops".
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Defense Reorganization Act of 1958 removed the power of command over troops from secretaries of military departments and service chiefs.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] A unified combatant command is a military command composed of personnel/equipment from at least two Military Departments, which has a broad, continuing mission.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] They are responsible for the operational command of forces.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Almost all operational U.S. forces are under the authority of a Unified Command.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The DoD Unified Command Plan lays out combatant commands' missions, geographical/functional responsibilities, and force structure.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] During military operations, the chain of command runs from the president to the secretary of defense to the combatant commanders of the Combatant Commands.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Department of Defense spending in 2017 was 3.15% of GDP and accounted for about 38% of the budgeted global military spending – more than the next seven largest militaries combined.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Beyond 2021 the 27th secretary of defense is projecting the need for yearly budget increases of 3 to 5 percent to modernize.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Department of Defense accounts for the majority of federal discretionary spending.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] In FY2017 (U.S. fiscal year 2017), the Department of Defense budgeted spending accounted for 15% of the U.S. federal budget, and 49% of federal discretionary spending, which represents funds not accounted for by pre-existing obligations.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Additionally, it does not account for defense spending outside of military operations, including expenditures by the Department of Homeland Security, counter-terrorism funding by the FBI, and intelligence-gathering spending by the NSA.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] In the 2010 United States federal budget, the Department of Defense was allocated a base budget of $533.7 billion, with a further $75.5 billion adjustment in respect of 2009, and $130 billion for overseas contingencies.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The subsequent 2010 Department of Defense Financial Report shows the total budgetary resources for FY2010 were $1.2 trillion.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Of these resources, $1.1 trillion were obligated and $994 billion were disbursed, with the remaining resources relating to multi-year modernization projects requiring additional time to procure.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] After over a decade of non-compliance, as part of the National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2010, Congress established a deadline of FY2017 for the Department of Defense to achieve audit readiness, although this did not end up occurring.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] In 2015 the allocation for the Department of Defense was $585 billion, the highest level of budgetary resources among all federal agencies, and this amounts to more than one-half of the annual federal expenditures in the United States federal budget discretionary budget.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] On 28 September 2018, President Donald Trump signed the Department of Defense and Labor, Health and Human Services, and Education Appropriations Act, 2019, and Continuing Appropriations Act, 2019 (H.R.6157) into law.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] On 30 September 2018, the FY2018 Budget expired and the FY2019 budget came into effect.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The FY2019 Budget for the Department of Defense is approximately $686,074,048,000 (including Base + Overseas Contingency Operations + Emergency Funds) in discretionary spending and $8,992,000,000 in mandatory spending totaling $695,066,000,000.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Undersecretary of Defense (Comptroller) David L.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Norquist said in a hearing regarding the FY 2019 budget: "The overall number you often hear is $716 billion.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] That is the amount of funding for national defense, the accounting code is 050 and includes more than simply the Department of Defense.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] It includes, for example, the Department of Energy and others.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] That large a number, if you back out the $30 billion for non-defense agencies, you get to $686 billion.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] That is the funding for the Department of Defense, split between $617 billion in base and $69 billion in overseas contingency".
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Department of Defense budget encompasses the majority of the National Defense Budget of approximately $716.0 billion in discretionary spending and $10.8 billion in mandatory spending for a $726.8 billion total.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Of the total, $708.1 billion falls under the jurisdiction of the House Committee on Armed Services and Senate Armed Services Committee and is subject to authorization by the annual National Defense Authorization Act (NDAA).
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The remaining $7.9 billion falls under the jurisdiction of other congressional committees.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Department of Defense is unique because it is one of the few federal entities where the majority of its funding falls into the discretionary category.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The majority of the entire federal budget is mandatory, and much of the discretionary funding in the budget consists of DoD dollars.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] As of 10 March 2023 the FY2024 presidential budget request was $842 billion.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] On 3 June 2023, the debt ceiling was suspended until 2025.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The $886 billion National Defense Authorization Act is facing reconciliation of the House and Senate bills after passing both houses 27 July 2023; the conferees have to be chosen, next.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] As of September 2023, a continuing resolution was needed to prevent a government shutdown.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] A shutdown was avoided on 30 September for 45 days (until 17 November 2023), with passage of the NDAA on 14 December 2023.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Senate will next undertake negotiations on supplemental spending for 2024.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] A government shutdown was averted on 23 March 2024 with the signing of a $1.2 trillion bill to cover FY2024.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] A 2013 *Reuters* investigation concluded that Defense Finance and Accounting Service, the primary financial management arm of the Department of Defense, implements monthly "unsubstantiated change actions"—illegal, inaccurate "plugs"—that forcibly make DoD's books match Treasury's books.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] Reuters reported that the Pentagon was the only federal agency that had not released annual audits as required by a 1992 law.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] According to Reuters, the Pentagon "annually reports to Congress that its books are in such disarray that an audit is impossible".
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] In 2015, a Pentagon consulting firm performed an audit on the department's budget.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] It found that there was $125 billion in wasteful spending that could be saved over the next five years without layoffs or reduction in military personnel.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] In 2016, *The Washington Post* uncovered that rather than taking the advice of the auditing firm, senior defense officials suppressed and hid the report from the public to avoid political scrutiny.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] In June 2016, the Office of the Inspector General released a report stating that the Army made $6.5 trillion in wrongful adjustments to its accounting entries in 2015.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The Department of Defense failed its fifth audit in 2022, and could not account for more than 60% of its $3.5 trillion in assets.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] In the latest Center for Effective Government analysis of 15 federal agencies which receive the most Freedom of Information Act requests, published in 2015 (using 2012 and 2013 data, the most recent years available), the DoD earned 61 out of a possible 100 points, a D− grade.
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] While it had improved from a failing grade in 2013, it still had low scores in processing requests (55%) and disclosure rules (42%).
[src:ada-deep/united-states-department-of-defense] The organization and functions of the Department of Defense are in Title 10 of the United States Code.
